  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7db1e36e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# HD143006 Tutorial Part 1\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we are going to do the first step in real world data analysis with MPoL. We will gather the data and then produce a diagnostic image-- the MPoL Dirty Image. This image will have no RML methods applied to it, but it is still a good preliminary checkpoint. We will see the quality of this image and compare it to the DSHARP image created using the CLEAN method ([Andrews et al. 2018](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...869L..41A/abstract)).\n",
    "\n",
    "### Introduction to Regularized Maximum Likelihood (RML) Imaging\n",
    "\n",
    "Regularized Maximum Likelihood (RML) imaging is a forward modeling methodology. We predict an image then represent it as an array of pixels. This is brought to the visibility domain through a forward Fourier tranform. This is then compared to the measured data to ensure it is a viable predicted image. Due to information loss of the true image when obtaining the measured data, several predicted images- including incorrect ones- will match. To get to our best predicted image, we make new predictions by choosing the most likely (Maximum Likelihood) configuration and favoring specified criterion (Regularized). The likeliness and how well a predicted image meets a certain criterion is mathematically represented in a loss function. We minimize the loss function by changing pixel parameters in the predicted image, giving us the best version of the predicted image.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Loading Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's load the data as we've done in previous tutorials. We will be examining the Fiducial Images (.fits) and Extracted Visibilities (.npz) of the HD143006 DSHARP survey. The extracted visibilities were calculated from the Final Calibrated Measurement Sets from DSHARP [here](https://mpol-dev.github.io/visread/) using visread.\n",
    "\n",
    "*You can either download these two files (HD143006_continuum.fits and HD143006_continuum.npz) directly to your working directory, or use astropy to download them during run time.*\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "4e4ccf5b",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:42:06.939440Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:42:06.938839Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:42:07.099325Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:42:07.098720Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from astropy.io import fits\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from astropy.utils.data import download_file"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "811ab262",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:42:07.103765Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:42:07.103148Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:42:12.471830Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:42:12.471287Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# downloading fits file\n",
    "fname_F = download_file(\n",
    "   'https://almascience.eso.org/almadata/lp/DSHARP/images/HD143006_continuum.fits',\n",
    "   cache=True,\n",
    "   pkgname='mpol',\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "id": "d22f3262",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:42:12.478086Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:42:12.477383Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.205424Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.207160Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# downloading extracted visibilities file\n",
    "fname_EV = download_file(\n",
    "    'https://zenodo.org/record/4904794/files/HD143006_continuum.npz',\n",
    "    cache=True,\n",
    "    pkgname='mpol',\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "80051c7b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have the files, let us examine the fits image created by the DSHARP team using the CLEAN algorithm ([Andrews et al. 2018](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...869L..41A/abstract)). First let's extract our data and then, to properly display the image, we will need to change from units of pixels to arcseconds. To do this, we will calculate the image extent."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "b46f3d31",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.214184Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.211266Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.217598Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.216966Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# opening the fits file\n",
    "dfits = fits.open(fname_F)\n",
    "# getting the data from the fits file\n",
    "clean_fits = dfits[0].data\n",
    "header = dfits[0].header\n",
    "# closing fits file\n",
    "dfits.close()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "df6a7e01",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.225622Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.224210Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.226347Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.226950Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# the following is to make axis scaling in arcsec (calculating the image extent)\n",
    "# get the number of pixels in each direction\n",
    "nx = header[\"NAXIS1\"]\n",
    "ny = header[\"NAXIS2\"]\n",
    "# RA coordinates\n",
    "CDELT1 = 3600 * header[\"CDELT1\"]  # Convert from decimal scaling to arcsec\n",
    "# DEC coordinates\n",
    "CDELT2 = 3600 * header[\"CDELT2\"]  # [arcsec]\n",
    "RA = (np.arange(nx) - nx / 2) * CDELT1  # [arcsec]\n",
    "DEC = (np.arange(ny) - ny / 2) * CDELT2  # [arcsec]\n",
    "# extent needs to include extra half-pixels.\n",
    "# RA, DEC are pixel centers\n",
    "ext = (\n",
    "    RA[0] - CDELT1 / 2,\n",
    "    RA[-1] + CDELT1 / 2,\n",
    "    DEC[0] - CDELT2 / 2,\n",
    "    DEC[-1] + CDELT2 / 2,\n",
    ")  # [arcsec]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "8ccf7350",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.256797Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:43:14.256136Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:43:15.205898Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:43:15.205361Z"
    }
   },

    "# plotting the clean fits\n",
    "plt.imshow(np.squeeze(clean_fits), origin='lower', extent=ext)\n",
    "# limiting the x and y axes so that we only plot the disk\n",
    "plt.xlim(left=0.75, right=-0.75)\n",
    "plt.ylim(top=0.75, bottom=-0.75)\n",
    "# axis labels\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$\\Delta \\alpha \\cos \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",

   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "08f7b97b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This is the image produced by the CLEAN algorithm used by the DSHARP team.  In Part 1 of this tutorial we will be creating an MPoL Gridder object and  the diagnostic dirty image. [**Part 2**](https://mpol-dev.github.io/MPoL/tutorials/HD143006_Part_2.html) of the tutorial will cover the optimization loop of the model to create the RML image.\n",
    "\n",
    "To create the dirty image, we will use the extracted visibilities from the npz file and the MPoL Gridder and Coordinates packages.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "a59b2af2",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:43:15.211970Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:43:15.211337Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:43:17.631511Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:43:17.632298Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# load extracted visibilities from npz file\n",
    "dnpz = np.load(fname_EV)\n",
    "uu = dnpz['uu']\n",
    "vv = dnpz['vv']\n",
    "weight = dnpz['weight']\n",
    "data = dnpz['data']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ddf230ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's quickly plot the U,V visibilities as seen in the [Cross Validation Tutorial](https://mpol-dev.github.io/MPoL/tutorials/crossvalidation.html) and the [Visread docs](https://mpol-dev.github.io/visread/tutorials/introduction_to_casatools.html#Get-the-baselines)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "95241bc4",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:43:17.660975Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:43:17.652611Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.624026Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.624526Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0.5, 1.0, '$U$, $V$ Visibilities')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

     },

       "width": 515
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1)\n",
    "ax.scatter(uu,vv, s=.5, rasterized=True, linewidths=0.0, c='k')\n",
    "ax.scatter(-uu,-vv, s=.5, rasterized=True, linewidths=0.0, c='k')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(r\"$u$ [k$\\lambda$]\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(r\"$v$ [k$\\lambda$]\")\n",
    "ax.set_title(r'$U$, $V$ Visibilities')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0b683f6f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As you can see, there are very few visibilities > 7,000 ($k\\lambda$), and a very dense region of visibilities between -2000 and 2000 ($k\\lambda$). This indicates outliers at the higher frequencies while the bulk of our data stems from these lower frequencies."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d43674bf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To create the MPoL Gridder object, we need a `cell_size` and the number of pixels in the width of our image, `npix`. You can read more about these properties in the [GridCoords](https://mpol-dev.github.io/MPoL/api.html#mpol.coordinates.GridCoords) API Documentation.  In the fits header we see our image is 3000x3000 pixels, so `npix=3000`. Getting our cell size in terms of arcseconds is a bit more tricky. Our fits image has a header called `CDELT1` which is the scaling in degrees. To get this into arcseconds we multiply by 3600. We save this as `cdelt_scaling`. `cdelt_scaling` can be negative, and cell_size must be positive so we will take the absolute value of this."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "9ec7c393",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.629743Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.628975Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.635767Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.635245Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Filename: /home/runner/.mpol/cache/download/url/3e5b682bb9f1ea6e13cfe13e03d1170e/contents\n",
      "No.    Name      Ver    Type      Cards   Dimensions   Format\n",
      "  0  PRIMARY       1 PrimaryHDU      80   (3000, 3000, 1, 1)   float32   \n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# opening the fits file\n",
    "dfits = fits.open(fname_F)\n",
    "# printing out the header info\n",
    "dfits.info()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "27881330",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.641893Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.640398Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.642603Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.643116Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cdelt_scaling = dfits[0].header['CDELT1'] * 3600 # scaling [arcsec]\n",
    "cell_size = abs(cdelt_scaling) # [arcsec]\n",
    "# closing fits file\n",
    "dfits.close()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "2f338fb4",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.647214Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:44:12.646584Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:44:13.148512Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:44:13.147836Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from mpol import gridding, coordinates"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "22fee741",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2021-06-17T20:44:13.153839Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2021-06-17T20:44:13.153222Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2021-06-17T20:44:28.318654Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2021-06-17T20:44:28.315236Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# creating Gridder object\n",
    "data_re = data.real\n",
    "data_im = data.imag\n",
    "coords = coordinates.GridCoords(cell_size=cell_size, npix=512)\n",
    "gridder = gridding.Gridder(\n",
    "    coords=coords,\n",
    "    uu=uu,\n",
    "    vv=vv,\n",
    "    weight=weight,\n",
    "    data_re=data_re, # separating the real and imaginary values of our data\n",
    "    data_im=data_im\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ac0fd65",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We now have everything we need to get the MPoL dirty image. No RML methods will be applied in Part 1 of this tutorial. Here we are using [Gridder.get_dirty_image()](../api.rst#mpol.gridding.Gridder.get_dirty_image) to average the visibilities to the grid defined by gridder and from there we get our dirty image and dirty beam. There are different ways to average the visibilities, called weighting, and here we use Uniform and Briggs weighting to find and produce a dirty image that resembles the CLEAN image. More info on the weighting can be read in the [CASA documentation](https://casa.nrao.edu/casadocs-devel/stable/imaging/synthesis-imaging/data-weighting). For the Briggs weighting, we will use three different values for the `robust` variable. This dictates how aggresive our weight scaling is towards image resolution or image sensitivity.\n",
    "\n",
    "*Note: when `robust=-2.0` the result is similar to that of the Uniform scale*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "181d5331",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Great! Now let's make a plotting function to show us the MPoL dirty image. If you have read through other MPoL tutorials, then this code should look familiar. We are going to plot all four of the different weightings, so creating a plotting function simplifies our code a lot.\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot(img, imtitle=\"image\"):\n",
    "    kw = {\"origin\": \"lower\", \"extent\": gridder.coords.img_ext}\n",
    "    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=1)\n",
    "    im = ax.imshow(np.squeeze(img), **kw)\n",
    "    plt.colorbar(im)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(imtitle)\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel(r\"$\\Delta \\alpha \\cos \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel(r\"$\\Delta \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "    plt.xlim(left=.75, right=-.75)\n",
    "    plt.ylim(bottom=-.75, top=.75)\n",
    "\n",
    "img, beam = gridder.get_dirty_image(weighting='uniform')\n",
    "img1, beam1 = gridder.get_dirty_image(weighting=\"briggs\", robust=1.0, unit=\"Jy/arcsec^2\")\n",
    "img2, beam2 = gridder.get_dirty_image(weighting=\"briggs\", robust=0.0, unit=\"Jy/arcsec^2\")\n",
    "img3, beam3 = gridder.get_dirty_image(weighting=\"briggs\", robust=-1.0, unit=\"Jy/arcsec^2\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plot(img, imtitle=\"uniform\")\n",
    "plot(img1, imtitle=\"robust_1.0\")\n",
    "plot(img2, imtitle=\"robust_0\")\n",
    "plot(img3, imtitle=\"robust_-1.0\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Below we plot the DSHARP CLEAN image alongside the MPoL Dirty Image weighted with the Briggs scale and `robust=0.0` for comparison.\n",
    "\n",
    "kw = {\"origin\": \"lower\", \"extent\": gridder.coords.img_ext}\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows = 2)\n",
    "ax[0].imshow(np.squeeze(clean_fits), origin='lower', extent=ext)\n",
    "ax[0].set_xlim(left=.75, right=-.75)\n",
    "ax[0].set_ylim(bottom=-.75, top=.75)\n",
    "ax[0].set_title('DSHARP CLEAN Image')\n",
    "ax[0].set_xlabel(r\"$\\Delta \\alpha \\cos \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "ax[0].set_ylabel(r\"$\\Delta \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "ax[1].imshow(np.squeeze(img), **kw)\n",
    "ax[1].set_title('MPoL Dirty Image')\n",
    "ax[1].set_xlim(left=.75, right=-.75)\n",
    "ax[1].set_ylim(bottom=-.75, top=.75)\n",
    "ax[1].set_xlabel(r\"$\\Delta \\alpha \\cos \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "ax[1].set_ylabel(r\"$\\Delta \\delta$ [${}^{\\prime\\prime}$]\")\n",
    "fig.set_figheight(10)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b15f08aa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As you can see there are many similarities between the diagnostic dirty image and the image produced by the DSHARP survey using the CLEAN algorithm ([Andrews et al. 2018](https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...869L..41A/abstract)). While the dirty image is more noisy, it still maintains many distinct features present in the CLEAN image. In the next part of the HD143006 tutorial, we will be cleaning the diagnostic dirty image using RML through Neural Networks, Optimization, and Cross Validation with help from [PyTorch](pytorch.org).\n"
   ]
  }
